{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"7002049f-e48b-4324-8c65-dbba196cd7be","content":"Use **`dotnet run`**, not `dotnet test`.\n\nHot reload with `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.HotReload` requires running the test project directly as an executable:\n\n```bash\nDOTNET_WATCH_SUPPRESS_LAUNCH_BROWSER=1 dotnet watch run --project TestProject.csproj\n```\n\nOr simply:\n\n```bash\ndotnet watch run\n```\n\n**Why not `dotnet test`?** The hot reload extension works with the Microsoft Testing Platform (`TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport`), which makes your test project a standalone executable. `dotnet watch run` monitors for file changes and re-executes tests automatically, enabling the hot reload loop. `dotnet test` doesn't support the watch/hot reload workflow.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ebf2c1e1-d55e-41d8-8573-7708724e35a8","outputTokens":176,"requestId":"042A:1EAE:310FA0:428B89:69E8245F"},"id":"e498b569-a4c1-4d68-ae21-c989011034c0","timestamp":"2026-04-22T01:29:09.560Z","parentId":"dc862503-4822-461f-8482-a3434d32bb24"}
